<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>06 September 2013</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Submission from the Confederation of British Industry</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The CBI is the UK’s leading business organisation, speaking for some 240,000 businesses tha</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">t together employ around a third of the private sector workforce. With offices across the UK as well as representation in Brussels, Washington, Beijing and Delhi the CBI communicates the British business voice around the world. Our members </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">include businesses from a number of sectors which are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> commercial partners with local authorities on contracts ranging from waste collection and HR functions right through to the management of whole frontline services. Our submission reflects their experiences.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We are pleased to have the opportunity to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> provide evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">on local government procurement. The public sector spends around £230</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">bn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> every year on goods and services and two thirds of that is spent by local authorities. To ensure value at a time of lower spending, authorities need procurement processes that select the best provider at the best price and encourage investment in new services that meet defined outcomes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">It is crucial that procurement is considered not in isolation but as part of a longer-term shift in councils, from being primarily a provider of service to becoming a commissioner of services. The challenge of austerity is often a temptation to see procurement as a vehicle simply to reduce costs, rather than as part of a bigger process of re-thinking how services operate.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">he CBI believes there are a number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">factors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> which should be considered within the current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">There is a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> mixed picture of procurement performance across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local authorities need to shift</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">primary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">provider to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">commissioner of services and develop the necessary toolkit of skills and processes to act as an effective market steward</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improving tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ansparency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> is an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> essential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tool in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> building trust in markets and making them sustainable</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Developing the capacity of SMEs to participate in public sector procurements is essential, but will take time – councils can support it without undermining the existing market</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">re is a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline"> mixed picture of procurement performance across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">There is no single picture of performance across all 353</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> councils in England and Wales as e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">faces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> a different set of challenges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ome are relatively well placed and have the organisational ‘headroom’ to consider change; others are looking simply at the year ahead.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Councils need to adopt procurement processes that are fit for purpose in a lower spending era. Many have well-used procurement models for existing services with well-understood specifications. Partnering for the long-term, particularly for people-based services, requires a different approach. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Members also report that many councils still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">don’t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> undertake sufficient preparation for many tendering process.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">There is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">however</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> no</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> standard picture of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the average time and costs of procurement; members report a wide variation in the performance of councils. On the whole UK procurements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">take </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">on average </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">50% longer than those in Germany or France, so despite the variation there is a clear pressure on local authorities to improve how they manage the functional process of procurement.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">There is also a clear link between the length of the procurement (and the intensity of the process) and final costs. For example, one construction member spends on average £8,000 on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">pre-qualification questionnaire</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> for a basic assessment; the company responded to around 200 tenders a year, meaning £1.6m is spent on pre-qualification alone for the projects it pursues.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Councils often don’t remember that the private sector has to just</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ify</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the attractiveness of a contract and the likelihood of winning to test whether the bidding costs are worthwhile. They should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">seek to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">minimise the time and cost involved in bidding as to attract the biggest pool of potential bidders.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 3.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">Local authorities need to shift from primary pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">vider to commissioner of service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">s and develop the necessary toolkit of skills and processes to act as an effective market steward</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Within the context of constrained spending there is an imperative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">on councils to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> change how they operate as commercial partners in the market place.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">emographic changes and increased demands for public services are unavoidable over the long term; re-thinking how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a council </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">operates as a customer is part of facing up to this challenge.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ouncils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">need to understand and communicate throughout their organisations what they need to achieve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> understand the costs of doing do so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and the capacity of the existing market to meet that need. This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> early strategic thinking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> is also the point at which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">council can introduce objectives relating to creating social value and supporting specific</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> sectors as part of an overall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> industrial strateg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and engage the market on solutions that can respond</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Councils should increasingly see their organisation as a market maker, engaging appropriately with potential providers throughout the commissioning process. Feedback from our members indicates that there is recognition from authorities that commissioning is becoming a strategic activity for them. As such, it becomes more than simply a question of successful procurement; commercial and policy teams must host a more intelligent conversation with the market. There is a ‘toolkit’ of important processes and behaviours which councils will need:</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">An improved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> skillset </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> local authority commercial teams </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> allow them to be better market managers</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Better strategic leadership of major change programmes to ensure the desired outcomes from a procurement process</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A stronger understanding of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">how the provider market operates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ensure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> councils develop the most effective partnerships and manage risk effectively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></li></ol></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">There is much welcome evidence of councils being more creative in jointly commissioning key services.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">LGA figures show that efficiency savings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">so far </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">made through shared services are close to £280m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. At least 337 councils across the country</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> are involved in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">325 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">shared-service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> agreement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ooling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">functional services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> like HR and fin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ance functions is sensible and in this area local government procurement teams are often ahead of the curve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">For example, the Tri-Borough area of Kensington &amp; Chelsea, Westminster and Hammersmith</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> &amp; Fulham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">partners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">an external provider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> on a £150m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> ten-year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> contract for facilities management across 2,000 buildings comprising 1.3 million square feet. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">This contract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> is expected to deliver efficiency savings of more than £2m annually to each of the boroughs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ther London boroughs and schools have the opportunity to buy into the se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">rvice as partnering authorities, creating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> opportunit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">growth. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Other councils adopting a shared model include </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Northampton and Daventry councils sharing environmental services effectively and Sussex, Surrey and Hampshire police authorities sharing air support.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Yet there are still councils who are not yet sharing any services across boundaries. In many cases, the reality of political priorities and territoriality will often run counter to best practice in procurement, and the CBI recognises there is no easy solution to overcome this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 3.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">An improved skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">et for local authority commercial teams will allow </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> to be better market managers</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">There are many excellent procurement and commercial professionals working in local government.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Over the next few years, they will be at the forefront of the development of new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> skills sets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">among council staff that allow councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> to manage markets effectively. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">e see four key areas where commercial teams </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">– and, ultimately, policy and service teams – can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">sharpen their capacity and knowledge:</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Analysing need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> – responding to demographic challenges and understand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> what people need</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Planning market interventions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> – not rushing into procurement, but having a richer dialogue with th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">e market about what’s possible</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">rocurement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> – reducing the length and cost of procurements to encourage SMEs bid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">; improving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the use of framework contracts and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">managing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> risks of performance failure</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Reviewing performance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> looking at how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">contracts have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> performed and learning lessons</span></li></ol></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Knowledge development is a two-way street. Many members already propose collaboration and secondments of council staff to contractors as an important part of any partnership arrangement, as this creates a positive route for sharing experiences and skills across both organisations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.25pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Contract management is an essential skill for councils to ensure value throughout the life of a contract. Monitoring performance and good continuity regimes are important to identify and manage risks associated with the operation of any market, and to learn and apply the lessons from any failure.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">isk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">can be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> approached </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">something negativ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, to be mitigated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">here are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">as yet too </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">few processes for identifying opportunities which creates the space for innovation. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">isk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> can be shared</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> more effectively </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">between councils and contractors, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> phasing the amount </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">of risk which commissioners transfer to providers through schedules which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> utilise part-payment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">up front and for activities, to cover early start-up and running costs. Contracts, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">handled correctly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, can manage risk effectively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> but too many councils offer only short-term contracts to smaller providers to mitigate risks, which ultimately impede the contractor’s ability to achieve the defined outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">and increases costs.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Better </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">strategic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">leadership of major change programmes improves the likelihood of achieving the desire outcomes from a procurement process</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Council chief executives have many roles but their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">strategic involvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">procurement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> will become increasingly important. Some have begun this process but there are still many that are too far removed from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">oversight of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">major commissioning projects.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> A chief executive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">sometimes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">need to be, in effect, a ‘chief commissioning officer’. Having a clear vision of what fundamental change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">is required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> (for example, changing the way adult social care is managed), and leading that vision internally, is essential to any successful </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">project</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ffective leadership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">on major commissioning project can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">create the ‘headroom’ in which a council can engage the market and think more expansively about how to achieve the outcomes it wants. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">This should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> set clear outcomes for any service and establish the criteria for ensuring how the service will run and the routes open in the case of provider failure on a cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">itical service. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">To give one example, CBI member Capita’s contract with Staffordshire County Council is a fully commercial joint venture between the company and the council, linked clearly to the latter’s strategic growth plan. Here, the chief executive is closely involved in the management of the contract and supported much of the early soft testing of the market. The contract does not require a lengthy list of KPIs because there is a shared imperative to achieve commercial growth in the services within the joint venture. The chief executive’s leadership was important in encouraging the shift from a contractor relationship to one of commercial partnership. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">A stronger u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">nderstanding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">of how the provider market operates, which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> ensures councils develop the most effective partnerships and manage risk effectively</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Both</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> commissioner and provider need to understand how each other operates.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">any councils still make incorrect assumptions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">about suppliers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> that limit their capacity to grow markets and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">identify</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the most effective solution to the service demand identified. For example:</span></li></ol><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 86pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. Much of the future investment in transforming public services will come from drawing on the private sector balance sheets and encouraging investment in the right projects. Yet many councils still tender contracts that don’t have the right commercial profile to attract that investment. Councils need to better understand the commercial imperatives that drive investment decisions</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 86pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Viability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. Some councils assume that the major providers will automatically bid for every contract. In fact, many larger providers frequently withdraw from bidding when an offer is commercially unattractive and will pick and choose the most commercially attractive projects to bid for. So commissioners cannot assume that the market will always respond to every tender, and must instead be more effective in selling projects to the market</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Poor procurement models</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. Construction companies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> that councils are still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">often </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">wedded to single-stage procurements for building projects, which give little scope for engaging first with the market on the project’s goals. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Some c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ouncils are signing contracts with providers who they’ve never talked to in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">detail about the contract. This approach is unlikely to deliver value and sustainability. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">he CBI is keen to see tenders constructed around clear goals, with contracts that can provide effective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">accountability for performance and stimulate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">innovative new approaches.</span></li></ol><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Members report a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> trend away from long-term (ten-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">year plus) contracts from counci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ls, in favour of shorter (three-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">year) contracts, as a response to the perceived risk of being ‘stuck’ with a long-term contract that become</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> unaffordable. The experiences of councils like Sandwell have undoubtedly influenced many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">other councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> to eschew long</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">term contracts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. In that instance, the council </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">entered into a long-term contract with a provider that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">maintained the same level of charges following a reduction in staff,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> resulting in the council seeking to terminate the contract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The CBI understands the caution over long-term contracts, but a better model can be to move towards longer term contracts with performance breaks at shorter intervals, which provide that element of control but also ensure the contracts has the headroom to allow it to invest.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">There can be a tendency for local authorities to be risk averse around markets. It is right for councils to manage risk and accountability effectively. It can help if they look at risk in two ways in order to do so: the organisational risks associated with changes in services and functions to deliver better outcomes; and the risks associated with the process of tendering and going out to market.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">There is often still an assumption that most of that risk can be taken on by a private contractor. Councils must understand the capacity of contractors and acknowledge that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the level of risk has ramifications for how much investment – and therefore, transformation – can be achieved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Some c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ouncils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> contracting in a positive way to build in innovation and change from the start. Serco’s shared services partnership with Hertfordshire Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> includes an ‘innovation clause’ in the contract which stipulates a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> amount of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> innovation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and added value</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> adult socia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">l care provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> As a result, S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">erco created an eMarketplace </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> residents in conjunction with local voluntary organisa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">tions to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> search for goods and services, compare prices, contact providers directly and rate those that they have used.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> 2012 report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Commissioning Dialogues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> identified that provider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and commissioners are not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">speaking the same language</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">’ on commissioning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and have different perceptions of what the priorities should be in any discussion with the market.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Good dialogue must be at the heart of any commissioning process, including the procurement stage, to address ‘stuck conversations’ between councils and providers on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> risk, openness and capacity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">CBI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> research identified a number of ways to change the nature of the conversation between commissioners and potential partners:</span></li></ol><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The wider adoption of a four-stage commissioning model (analyse/plan/do/review)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Earlier engagement of commissioners, service users and providers in the commissioning process, focused on analysis and planning </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Mutual understanding through diverse skills sets and viewpoints on both sides</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Better management of shared risk and accountability for performance. </span></li></ol><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">In so doing, procurement can – if used correctly – be an important tool </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">local government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">to drive wider economic and social value. The key is finding the right balance between setting challenging goals for providers and ensuring they can have the flexibility to innovate in service delivery – after all, this is why they are hired in the first place.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Creating incentives for providers to promote the use of apprenticeships and to contract with local firms at the pre-procurement stage is a positive step open to councils in discussions with the market. We believe that flexibility and innovation should be the watchwords in driving wider value, rather than mandating specific approaches in a contract – on the living wage, for example. Indeed, if government is too prescriptive in contracts, it risks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">over-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">burdening smaller business</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">es in particular, rather than supporting them.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">Improved transparency is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">essential to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">ol in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline"> building trust in markets and making them sustainable</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The CBI acknowledges there is a public interest in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">more transparent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> services to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">identify</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> good performance, value for money and encourage greater accountability to the public and democratic institutions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. People need to feel they can trust whoever provides a service they rely on and know that they are being managed effectively and their performance monitored. They also want to know their money is being well spent.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">In local government this is especially true. There are a number of high-profile examples where a lack of transparency in a council’s procurement process has damaged its trust with the local community</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. Transparency is essential to identifying poor standards and dealing with them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">: i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">t shouldn’t take a whistle blower to identify poor delivery.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Therefore, commissioners and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">oviders of all types need to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> be more open and transparent, but in a way that does not undermine the existing commercial basis on which contracts are made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. The CBI has developed with its members </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a common </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> on transparency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> which all types of provider can align</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, to help build public trust in market accountability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> statement of principles says:</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Commissioners should serve as single points of information for services that are delivered by the independent sector and providers must give them the information they need both to respond to enquiries and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">share information</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Though providers are not subject to the Freedom of Information Act (and should not be) they should abide by the exceptions it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">sets out for the public sector</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">nformation would not be released if it could have implications for national security or commercial confidentiality. Existing obligations under separate regulations, such as the Data</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Protection Act, would continue</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Contracts should not impede the publication of information provided by contractors</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Providers should provide commissioners with the information necessary to respond to public questions about performance</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Providers should respond in a reasonable time to requests for information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></li></ol></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Exceptions to this should be kept to a minimum and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">consistent across all sectors.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">Developing the capacity of SMEs to participate in public sector procurements is essential, but will take time – councils can support it without undermining the existing market</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We support diverse markets where the best provider provides, regardless of its size and sector. There are already many SMEs successfully delivering services directly or through a supply chain – they are an essential catalyst for innovation, challenge and bringing in local or specialist skills to a major policy delivery challenge. We support initiatives that improve the capacity of SMEs to develop new opportunities in public sector markets.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Existing procurement processes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> create significant challenges for small or medium-sized business, particularly around cash flow. If contracting takes nine months and revenues do not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">come through for another six months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> that is a significant challenge for the cash flow of any winnin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">g small enterprise to cope with and a factor in determining whether to bid.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We support councils’ active steps to make the procurement process easier for small and medium-sized businesses. Long-term pipelines, pre-procurement engagement, industry workshops, online portals, limiting over-reliance on credit scores and abolishing contract clauses that require national coverage when a project is a local one – these and other achievable steps will create tangible benefits for any SME deciding whether to bid or pass.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Many members working in public services use smaller and local suppliers extensively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. They observe a tendency in some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">councils to assume that ‘small is good’ as a way of promoting local suppliers through public procurement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">But tendering</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> ten contracts in place of one will require significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, creating additional costs without any guarantee of improved outcomes or the capacity of the SMEs to manage these contracts. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Instead, one solution for councils looking to boost their local economies is to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> commission </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> contractor to manage a discrete service and stipulate as part of the contract that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">provider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> must source a percentage of the work from local suppliers. Not only does this shift the costs and risks associated with SME procurement onto the supplier, it focuses the efforts of local companies on delivering a service without the costs and risks associated with being a sole contracted supplier. Risks associated with cash flow and quality assurance can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">often </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">be better managed by a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">larger </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">contract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">partner </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">financial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">capacity to do so.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CBI</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-variant:normal; font-weight:normal">06 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> CBI, Commissioning Dialogues, December 2012 </span><a href="http://www.cbi.org.uk/media/1884803/dec_2012_cbinlgn_commissioning_dialogues.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.cbi.org.uk/media/1884803/dec_2012_cbinlgn_commissioning_dialogues.pdf</span></a></p></body></html>